ategory:Japanese idol groups]]\n[[Category:J Storm]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Jin Akanishi]]\n", "name_user": "Beatrixx00", "label": "safe", "comment": "No linked sources", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KAT-TUN"}
{"title_page": "Grant Hill", "text_new": "{{Other people}}\n{{short description|Retired American basketball player}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Grant Hill\n| image = Grant Hill 2007-12-08.jpg\n| caption = Hill with the Suns in 2007\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 8\n| weight_lb = 225\n| team = Atlanta Hawks\n| position = Vice Chair of the Board\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1972|10|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Dallas, Texas]]\n| high_school = [[South Lakes High School|South Lakes]]<br />([[Reston, Virginia]])\n| college = [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] (1990\u20131994)\n| draft_year = 1994\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 3\n| draft_team = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| career_start = 1994\n| career_end = 2013\n| career_number = 33\n| career_position = [[Small forward]] / [[Shooting guard]]\n| years1 = {{nbay|1994|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1999|end}}\n| team1 = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|2000|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2006|end}}\n| team2 = [[Orlando Magic]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2007|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2011|end}}\n| team3 = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| years4 = {{nbay|2012|full=y}}\n| team4 = [[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n| highlights = \n* 7\u00d7 [[NBA All-Star Game|NBA All-Star]] ([[1995 NBA All-Star Game|1995]]\u2013[[1998 NBA All-Star Game|1998]], [[2000 NBA All-Star Game|2000]], [[2001 NBA All-Star Game|2001]], [[2005 NBA All-Star Game|2005]])\n* [[All-NBA First Team]] ([[1996\u201397 NBA season|1997]])\n* 4\u00d7 [[All-NBA Second Team]] ([[1995\u201396 NBA season|1996]], [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1998]]\u2013[[1999\u20132000 NBA season|2000]])\n* [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|NBA Co-Rookie of the Year]] ([[1994\u201395 NBA season|1995]])\n* [[NBA All-Rookie First Team]] (1995)\n* 3\u00d7 [[NBA Sportsmanship Award]] ([[2004\u201305 NBA season|2005]], [[2007\u201308 NBA season|2008]], [[2009\u201310 NBA season|2010]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of NCAA Men's Division I Basketball champions|NCAA champion]] ([[1991 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1991]], [[1992 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1992]])\n* Consensus first-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[1994 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1994]])\n* Consensus second-team [[1993 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American (1993)]]\n* [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|ACC Player of the Year]] (1994)\n* [[NABC Defensive Player of the Year]] (1993)\n* No. 33 [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball#Retired numbers|retired by Duke Blue Devils]]\n* Third-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1990)\n* [[Virginia Mr. Basketball]] (1990)\n| stats_league = NBA\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 17,137 (16.7 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 6,169 (6.0 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value = 4,252 (4.1 apg)\n| HOF_player=grant-hill\n| bbr = hillgr01\n| medal_templates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[Basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flagu|United States}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Atlanta]] | [[United States national basketball team|National team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Basketball at the 1991 Pan American Games|1991 Havana]]|National team}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Americas Under-18 Championship|FIBA Americas U18 Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIBA Americas Under-18 Championship|1990 Montevideo]]|National team}}\n| CBBASKHOF_year = 2014\n}}\n'''Grant Henry Hill''' (born October 5, 1972) is a retired American professional [[basketball]] player who is a co-owner of the [[Atlanta Hawks]]. After playing [[college basketball]] for [[Duke University]], Hill played for four teams in his professional career in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA): The [[Detroit Pistons]], the [[Orlando Magic]], the [[Phoenix Suns]], and the [[Los Angeles Clippers]]. For most of his career, he played the small forward position. Hill also co-hosts ''[[NBA Inside Stuff]]'' on [[NBA TV]].\n\nHill played basketball at [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke University]] for four years. He was the 1994 [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|ACC Player of the Year]], a two-time [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|NCAA All-American]], and a two-time [[List of NCAA Men's Division I Basketball champions|NCAA champion]]. Hill was touted as one of the best players in Duke history and as one of the greatest collegiate basketball players of his era.\n\nAfter graduating from Duke in 1994, Hill was selected by the [[Detroit Pistons]] with the third overall pick in the [[1994 NBA draft|NBA draft]]. He was the co-winner of the 1995 [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award]]. Early in his NBA career, Hill was widely considered to be one of the best all-around players in the game, often leading his team in points, [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] and [[assist (basketball)|assists]]. In his first six seasons in the NBA, Hill averaged 21.6 points, 7.9 rebounds, and 6.3 assists per game and made the Eastern Conference All-Star Team five times. However, the trajectory of his career was altered by a 2000 ankle injury. The injury continued to plague him for several years, led to a March 2003 surgery that was followed by life-threatening complications, and forced him to miss the entire 2003\u201304 season. In 2005, Hill made the Eastern Conference All-Star Team as a member of the Magic. He played in the Western Conference Finals in 2010 during his tenure with the Phoenix Suns. In the 12 seasons following his ankle injury, Hill averaged 13.1 points, 4.7 rebounds, and 2.6 assists per game. On June 1, 2013, Hill announced his retirement from the NBA. He is a seven-time [[NBA All-Star Game|NBA All-Star]], a five-time [[All-NBA]] selection, and a three-time winner of the [[NBA Sportsmanship Award]]. In 2018, he was inducted into the [[Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame]].\n\nAn ownership group including Hill and [[Tony Ressler]] purchased the [[Atlanta Hawks]] on June 24, 2015.\n\n==College basketball career==\n{{BLP sources section|date=November 2019}}\nWhen the time came to choose a college, Hill's mother told the [[Fox Sports (USA)|Fox Sports]] documentary ''[[Beyond the Glory]]'', that she wanted him to attend [[Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball|Georgetown]], while his father preferred the [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|University of North Carolina]]. Hill decided to attend [[Duke University]], playing four years with the [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Blue Devils]] and winning national titles in [[1991 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1991]] and [[1992 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1992]]. Duke became the first Division I program to win consecutive titles since [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA]] in [[1973 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1973]]. Despite losing two of the biggest contributors on the Blue Devils, [[Christian Laettner]] (in 1992) and [[Bobby Hurley]] (each of whom went on to play in the NBA), Hill led Duke to the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|championship game]] once again in [[1994 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1994]], but lost to [[Arkansas Razorbacks men's basketball|Arkansas]] [[1993\u201394 Arkansas Razorbacks men's basketball team|Razorbacks]]. Hill won the [[Henry Iba Corinthian Award]] as the nation's top defensive player in 1993, and in 1994 he was the [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] Player of the Year. During his collegiate career, Hill became the first player in ACC history to collect more than 1,900 points, 700 rebounds, 400 assists, 200 steals and 100 blocked shots. As a result of his successful college career, he became the eighth player in Duke history to have his jersey number (33) retired. After his freshman season at Duke, Hill played on the bronze medal-winning U.S. team at the [[1991 Pan American Games]], held in [[Havana]], Cuba.\n\nHill also is widely known for his role in a desperation play in an [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA tournament]] regional final against [[1991\u201392 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]] in 1992, which is considered by many to be [[The Shot (Duke\u2013Kentucky)|one of the greatest college basketball games of all time]]. With Duke down 103\u2013102 in [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] and 2.1 seconds remaining after Kentucky's [[Sean Woods]] hit a floater, an unguarded Hill heaved the in-bounds pass 75 feet across the court into the hands of Laettner, who dribbled once and spun before pulling up to make the game-winning jumper from just outside the free-throw line as time expired.\n\nTouted as one of the best players in Duke history, many went as far as to say that Hill was one of the greatest collegiate basketball players of his era.<ref>Brodess, Doug (October 24, 2011). [http://m.bleacherreport.com/articles/585454-simply-the-best-top-ten-duke-blue-devils-of-all-time/page/11 \"Duke Basketball: Top 10 Blue Devils of All Time\"]. ''[[Bleacher Report]]''. Retrieved March 28, 2016.</ref>\n\n==NBA career and Team USA (1994\u20132013)==\n{{BLP sources section|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Detroit Pistons (1994\u20132000)===\nHill was drafted by the [[1994\u201395 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit Pistons]] with the third pick in the [[1994 NBA draft|NBA draft]] after graduating from Duke in 1994. He generally played the small forward position during his NBA career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2013/08/versatile-nba-players-history/grant-hill|title=The 25 Most Versatile Players in NBA History|last=Sibor|first=Doug|work=Complex.com|date=August 14, 2013|access-date=November 25, 2019}}</ref> In his first season, he averaged 19.9 points, 6.4 rebounds, 5.0 assists and 1.77 steals per game, and became the first Pistons rookie since [[Isiah Thomas]] in [[1981\u201382 NBA season|1981\u201382]] to score 1000 points. Hill ended up sharing [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award]] honors with [[Jason Kidd]] of the [[Dallas Mavericks]], becoming the first Piston since [[Dave Bing]] in [[1966\u201367 NBA season|1966\u201367]] to win the award. Hill also won the ''[[Sporting News]]'' Rookie of the Year Award. He was named to the all-NBA First Team in 1997, and all-NBA Second Teams in 1996, 1998, 1999 and 2000. Hill also regularly played in the [[National Basketball Association All-Star Game|NBA All-Star Game]], where he made history by being the first rookie to lead an NBA All-Star fan balloting in ([[1994\u201395 NBA season|1994\u201395]]) with 1,289,585 votes,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-6325252_ITM | work=Knight Ridder/Tribune News Service | title=Hill's record 1,289,585 votes will go down in all-star history. (Originated from Knight-Ridder Newspapers) | date=January 26, 1995}}</ref> narrowly defeating [[Shaquille O'Neal]]. In addition, he became the first rookie in any of the [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|four major professional sports leagues]] to lead all-star fan voting.\n\nIn his second season ([[1995\u201396 NBA season|1995\u201396]]), he once again led the All-Star fan balloting, this time edging [[Michael Jordan]] (Jordan's first All-Star game after returning since retiring in 1993). During the 1995\u201396 season, Hill showcased his all-round abilities by leading the NBA in [[triple-double]]s (10). He also won a [[gold medal]] at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta]] as a member of the [[United States men's national basketball team#1996 U.S. Olympic Basketball Team|U.S. men's basketball team]], where he had the team's fifth highest scoring average (9.7) and led the team in steals (18). In [[1996\u201397 NBA season|1996\u201397 season]], Hill averaged 21.4 points, 9.0 rebounds, 7.3 assists and 1.8 steals per game. He became the first player since [[Larry Bird]] in [[1989\u201390 NBA season|1989\u201390]] to average 20 points, 9 rebounds and 7 assists in a season, an accomplishment that had not been duplicated until [[Russell Westbrook]] averaged a triple-double in the [[2016-17 NBA season]]. Once again, Hill led the league in triple-doubles, where his 13 triple-doubles represented 35 percent of the league's triple-double total that season. He was the league's Player of the Month for January and was also awarded NBA's [[IBM Award]], given to the player with the biggest statistical contributions to his team. He finished third in [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] voting, behind [[Karl Malone]] and Michael Jordan.\n\nMuch like [[Scottie Pippen]] with the [[Chicago Bulls|Bulls]], Hill assumed the role of a \"[[point forward]]\" in Detroit, running the Pistons' offense. As a result, between the [[1995\u201396 NBA season|1995\u201396]] and [[1998\u201399 NBA season]]s, Hill was the league leader in assists per game among non-guards all four seasons. In the [[1998\u201399 NBA season|lockout-shortened 1999 season]], as he led his team in points, rebounds and assists for the third time, Hill joined [[Wilt Chamberlain]] and [[Elgin Baylor]] as the only players in NBA history to lead their teams in scoring, rebounding and assists more than once. Hill and Chamberlain are the only two players in league history to lead their teams in points, rebounds and assists per game three times. Hill was selected to play in the [[1998 FIBA World Championship]], but in the end no NBA players played in this tournament due to the [[lockout (industry)|lockout]].\n\nIn [[1999\u20132000 NBA season|1999\u20132000 season]], Hill averaged 25.8 points while shooting 49% from the field, the season's third highest scoring average, behind MVP [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and [[Allen Iverson]]. He averaged 6.6 rebounds and 5.2 assists per game. However, despite Hill's individual accomplishments in Detroit, the Pistons never made it far in the playoffs, either losing in the first round ([[1996 NBA Playoffs|1996]], [[1997 NBA Playoffs|1997]] and [[1999 NBA Playoffs|1999]]), or missing the playoffs entirely in the 1994\u201395 and [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1997\u201398 seasons]]. The [[2000 NBA Playoffs|2000 playoffs]] would be no different. On April 15, 2000, 7 days before the start of the playoffs, Hill sprained his left ankle in a game against the [[1999\u20132000 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]]. He continued to play until the first round playoff series against the [[1999\u20132000 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]], in which his injured ankle got worse and Hill was forced to leave halfway through game 2. Eventually, the Heat swept the Pistons 3\u20130. Hill was initially selected for the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Olympics]] U.S. team, but could not play due to the ankle injury. That ankle injury would prove to be a major liability for many years to come.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2014/03/17/grant-hill-on-wfan-ankle-nightmare-would-have-been-avoided-with-knicks/|title=Grant Hill: Ankle Nightmare Would Have Been Avoided With Knicks|date=March 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter the first six seasons of his career, before ankle injury, Hill had amassed a total of 9,393 points, 3,417 rebounds and 2,720 assists. [[Oscar Robertson]], Bird, and [[LeBron James]] are the only three players in league history to eclipse these numbers after their first six seasons.\n\n===Orlando Magic (2000\u20132007)===\nAs an unrestricted free agent, Hill had planned to sign with the [[2000\u201301 Orlando Magic season|Orlando Magic]]. On August 3, 2000, however, a sign-and-trade deal allowed Hill to receive a slightly more lucrative contract while Detroit received at least some compensation for losing him. The Pistons signed Hill to a seven-year, $92.8 million contract and traded him to Orlando for [[Chucky Atkins]] and [[Ben Wallace]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Magic's Strength No Illusion|date = August 3, 2000|url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/magics-strength-no-illusion/|work = CBS News|accessdate=April 1, 2018}}</ref> The Magic hoped he would team up with budding superstar [[Tracy McGrady]], who had been signed away from the [[Toronto Raptors]] at that time, to return Orlando among the NBA elite. But Hill was hampered by ankle injuries, playing in only four games in his [[2000\u201301 NBA season|first]] season with the Magic, 14 games in his [[2001\u201302 NBA season|second]] and 29 in his [[2002\u201303 NBA season|third]]. He was forced to sit out his ''entire'' fourth year with Orlando ([[2003\u201304 NBA season|2003\u201304]]). Meanwhile, the Pistons, who had defeated the Magic in the [[2003 NBA Playoffs|2003 Playoffs]], but ended up losing to the New Jersey Nets in the Eastern Conference Finals, won the championship the following year in [[2003\u201304 NBA season|2004]].\n\nGrant was a Yes Man. In 7617 He and Obama cured world hunger. During this time he also became a dinasourse and sailed title waves. Yes Titan like the book. Now in 5567 Grant hill became a world wide phenom when making soda that had soda in it. Use promo code sal at checkout for all your basketball needs. Yes so Lebanon James was the world champ in 15bc when he dunked over Jesus in the NFC championship game. Then when a rock hit his head he went into a comma lama drip i got that pirate drip. Grant cursed aids.\n\nIn March 2003, Hill underwent a major surgical procedure in which doctors re-fractured his ankle and realigned it with his leg bone. Five days after the surgery was performed, Hill developed a 104.5&nbsp;\u00b0F (40.3&nbsp;\u00b0C) [[fever]] and [[convulsion]]s, and was rushed to a hospital. Doctors removed the splint around his ankle and discovered that Hill had contracted a potentially fatal [[methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus|methicillin-resistant ''Staphylococcus aureus'']] (MRSA) infection. He was hospitalized for a week and had to take [[intravenous]] [[antibiotics]] for six months.\n\nIn the [[2004\u201305 NBA season|2004\u201305 season]] Hill, though hampered by a bruised left shin that caused him to miss several games, started and played 67 games for the Magic. He was named the Eastern Conference player of the week for the week between November 15\u201321, 2004. Over the season, Hill averaged 19.7 points per game on a .509 field goal percentage. Fans voted him an All-Star starter again, and he led the Eastern Conference All-Star Team to a victory over the West. In addition, at the conclusion of the season, Hill was awarded the [[Joe Dumars Trophy]] presented to the [[NBA Sportsmanship Award]] Winner.\n\nDuring the [[2005\u201306 NBA season|2005\u201306 season]] Hill was once again injured frequently as nagging groin injuries kept him sidelined for much of the first half of the season, limiting him to 21 games. He got a sports [[hernia]] that was caused by an uneven pressure on Hill's feet while he was running, due to concerns that he could re-aggravate the injury on his left ankle if it got too much pressure. Hill underwent surgery for the hernia and stated that he would consider retirement if he had to get another surgery.\n\nIn the [[2006\u201307 NBA season|2006\u201307 season]] Hill returned from injuries despite numerous rumors surrounding his retirement. Hill received ankle rotation therapy from specialists in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]] during the off-season and stated that he had regained much motion in his left ankle. Hill returned to the Magic lineup, starting at the [[shooting guard]] position. Despite having problems with injuries to his left knee and a [[tendon]] in his left ankle, Hill managed to play 65 games, two short of the highest number of games he played over a single season as a member of the Magic. He finished the season with averages of 14.4 points, 3.6 rebounds and 2.1 assists per game. This season would see Hill return to the playoffs for the first time since 2000, his first playoff appearance with the Magic. The 8th seed Magic would meet Hill's old team, the [[2006\u201307 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit Pistons]], in the first round. The Pistons' vast playoff experience would prevail over the inexperienced Magic, who had not seen significant post-season action for some years, and despite having some close games, the series would end with a 4\u20130 Pistons sweep, leaving Hill undecided on whether to return for the [[2007\u201308 NBA season|2007\u201308 season]] with the Magic, sign with another team, or retire.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/playoffs2007/news/story?id=2852728 Beset by injuries in career, Hill considers retirement], updated April 28, 2007</ref>\n\n===Phoenix Suns (2007\u20132012)===\n[[File:Grant Hill Phoenix.jpg|thumb|right|Hill with the Phoenix Suns in 2009]]\nHill became an [[unrestricted free agent]] on July 1, 2007. On July 5 Hill's agent, [[Lon Babby]], said Hill intended to sign with the [[2007\u201308 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix Suns]] on July 11 (the first day free agents can officially sign contracts).<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2926650 Hill to sign with Phoenix after agreeing to two-year deal] July 5, 2007</ref> Hill earned $1.83 million for [[2007\u201308 NBA season|2007\u201308]] with a $1.97 million player option for the next year. Hill was named captain along with [[Steve Nash]]. Hill was given permission by [[Phoenix Suns Ring of Honor|Suns Ring of Honor]] member, [[Alvan Adams]], to wear his familiar No. 33 with the Suns. Hill adapted well to the Suns' up-tempo style, averaging double figures in points as a key role player for Phoenix in the early months of the 2007\u201308 season. He played in the team's first 34 games before an emergency appendectomy on January 9, 2008, sidelined him for two weeks. Despite being bothered by multiple injuries throughout the season, Hill had his first 70-game season since leaving Detroit, averaging 13.1 ppg, 5.0 rpg and 2.9 apg in the process.\n\nPlaying for the Phoenix Suns in the 2008\u20132009 season, Hill appeared in all 82 games for the first time in his career and averaged 12.0 ppg, 4.90 rpg, and 2.3 apg, scoring 27 points and 10 rebounds in the Suns' season finale.\n\nOn July 10, 2009, the [[Associated Press]] reported that Hill decided to re-sign with the Phoenix Suns for a 2-year deal, despite an offer from the [[2009\u201310 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]] for the full mid-level exception and the [[2009\u201310 Boston Celtics season|Boston Celtics]] offering Hill the bi-annual exception.<ref>Aldridge, David. [http://www.nba.com/2009/news/features/david_aldridge/07/10/hill.suns/index.html \"Loyalty to Suns keeps Hill in Phoenix\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714183853/http://www.nba.com/2009/news/features/david_aldridge/07/10/hill.suns/index.html |date=July 14, 2009 }}, NBA.com, July 10, 2009.</ref>  The first year of the contract is believed to be worth around $3 million with the second year at Hill's option.\n\nIn 2010 the Phoenix Suns advanced to the Western Conference Semifinals, marking Hill's first playoff series victory, and making him the first NBA player in history to win his first playoff series after 15 years in the league.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} After sweeping the [[2009\u201310 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]] 4\u20130, the Suns then moved to the Western Conference Finals to face the [[2009\u201310 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]], but lost in six games (4-2).\n\nIn 2010, he was chosen as the tenth-smartest athlete in sports by ''[[Sporting News]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/feed/2010-09/smart-athletes/story/sporting-news-names-the-20-smartest-athletes-in-sports |title=SN names the 20 smartest athletes in sports |work=Sporting News |date=September 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523023358/http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/feed/2010-09/smart-athletes/story/sporting-news-names-the-20-smartest-athletes-in-sports |archivedate=May 23, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"sportingnews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/feed/2010-09/smart-athletes/story/sporting-news-names-the-20-smartest-athletes-in-sports |title=SN names the 20 smartest athletes in sports \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sporting News |date=September 23, 2010 |accessdate=June 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523023358/http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/feed/2010-09/smart-athletes/story/sporting-news-names-the-20-smartest-athletes-in-sports |archivedate=May 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"sportingnews.com\"/>\n\nOn June 8 Hill exercised his option for the [[2010\u201311 NBA season|2010\u201311 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valleyofthesuns.com/2010/06/08/grant-hill-exercises-option/| title=Grant Hill swiftly exercises option, sends message about keeping team together |date=June 8, 2010|last=Schwartz |first=Michael |publisher=valleyofthesuns.com}}</ref> The Suns underwent two major roster changes in 2010\u201311. During the pre-season teammate [[Amar'e Stoudemire]] left for New York while [[Hedo T\u00fcrko\u011flu]], [[Josh Childress]] and [[Hakim Warrick]] joined the Suns; within a year they also were traded for three other players. Hill became one of seven all-time NBA players to average 13 or more points at 38 years of age or older. On January 15, 2011, Hill passed the 16,000 career points milestone in a win over the [[2010\u201311 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]].\n\nOn December 9, 2011, Hill decided to stay with the Phoenix Suns for one year, accepting a $6.5 million contract.<ref>[http://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/2011/12/09/20111209grant-hill-phoenix-suns-returns-one-year-contract.html Grant Hill staying with Phoenix Suns<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> By the end of the [[2011\u201312 NBA season|2011\u201312 season]], Hill had reached 17,000 career points, ending the season 78th on the all-time NBA scoring list (82nd NBA/ABA), 79th in career assists (83rd), and 66th in career steals (71st).\n\n===Los Angeles Clippers (2012\u20132013)===\nAfter his contract with the Suns expired, Hill was pursued by multiple contenders, including the [[2012\u201313 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]], [[2012\u201313 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]], [[2012\u201313 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]], [[2012\u201313 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]], and the [[2012\u201313 Oklahoma City Thunder season|Oklahoma City Thunder]]. On July 18, 2012, Hill signed a contract with the Clippers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/clippers/clippers-sign-seven-time-all-star-grant-hill|title=CLIPPERS SIGN SEVEN-TIME ALL-STAR GRANT HILL|work=NBA.com|date=July 18, 2012|accessdate=July 18, 2012}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Hill suffered a bruised bone in his right knee in the preseason which kept him out for three months. He then made his debut with the Clippers on January 12, 2013 against the [[2012\u201313 Orlando Magic season|Orlando Magic]]. During the 2012\u201313 season, he played only 29 games, averaging 3.2 ppg and 1.7 rpg in 15.1 mpg. The Clippers finished 56-26, fourth best in the Western Conference, and won the Pacific Division for the first time in franchise history. However, the Clippers fell to the [[2012\u201313 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis Grizzlies]] in a six-game series in the first round.{{Citation Needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Retirement (2013)===\n\nOn June 1, 2013, Hill announced his retirement from professional basketball after 19 seasons in the NBA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehoops.com/blog/?p=13397|title=Grant Hill retires from NBA basketball :InsideHoops|website=www.insidehoops.com|access-date=June 2, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924042612/http://www.insidehoops.com/blog/?p=13397|archive-date=September 24, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/nba/story/_/id/9332928/grant-hill-retires-nba-19-seasons|title=Grant Hill retires from NBA after 19 seasons|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn September 7, 2018, Hill was inducted into the [[Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/2018-basketball-hall-of-fame-induction-ceremony-grant-hill-thanks-coach-k-jason-kidd-jokes-with-dirk/|title=2018 Basketball Hall of Fame induction ceremony: Grant Hill thanks Coach K; Jason Kidd jokes with Dirk|website=CBSSports.com}}</ref>\n\n==Post-NBA career==\n[[File:1_grant_hill_2019.jpg|thumb|Hill covering Game 2 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]]]\nBeginning in 2013, Hill has hosted NBA Inside Stuff on NBA TV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2013/9/24/4767186/nba-tv-nba-inside-stuff-revival|title='NBA Inside Stuff' is back|first=Steve|last=Lepore|date=September 24, 2013|website=SBNation.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebiglead.com/2019/03/28/christian-laettner-the-shot-date/|title=Where Are They Now: 27 Years After Christian Laettner Made the [sic] \"The Shot\"|date=March 28, 2019}}</ref> He is also a sports broadcaster for CBS.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/news/how-grant-hill-went-from-having-no-clue-about-broadcasting-to-calling-the-final-four-183904288.html|title=How Grant Hill went from having 'no clue' about broadcasting to calling the Final Four|website=sports.yahoo.com}}</ref> In 2015, Hill was named to the lead announcing team for [[CBS Sports|CBS]] and [[Turner Sports]]' joint coverage of the [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament]], alongside March Madness stalwarts [[Jim Nantz]] and [[Bill Raftery]].<ref name=\"2015 Final Four\">{{cite news\n  | author = Chip Patterson\n  | title = 2015 Final Four: Bill Raftery, Grant Hill picked as game analysts\n  | publisher = CBS Sports\n  | url = http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/eye-on-college-basketball/25026294/final-four-bill-raftery-grant-hill-picked-as-game-analysts\n  | date = February 3, 2015\n  | accessdate = March 11, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nOn June 24, 2015, a deal was approved by the NBA Board of Governors to sell the [[Atlanta Hawks]] franchise for $850 million to a group led by [[Tony Ressler]]. Hill was a member of that group, and he thus became a co-owner of the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afro.com/grant-hill-among-new-owners-of-atlanta-hawks/|title=Grant Hill Among New Owners of Atlanta Hawks - Afro|first=Stephanie|last=Cornish|date=April 25, 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2015/04/22/atlanta-hawks-sold-to-ares-ressler-for-730-million.html|title=Atlanta Hawks Sold to Ares' Ressler for $850 million, Group Includes Sara Blakely and Grant Hill|publisher=Atlanta Business Chronicle |date=April 24, 2015|access-date=January 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/atlanta-hawks-selling-for-850-million-1429732095 Atlanta Hawks Selling for $850 Million]. The Wall Street Journal. Ben Cohen. April 22, 2015. accessed February 9, 2016</ref><ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/news/videos/2019-02-15/grant-hill-on-fan-engagement-hawks-ownership-video</ref>\n\n==Sponsorships and paid endorsements==\n* In the 1990s, one of the soft drink [[Sprite (soft drink)|Sprite]]'s longest-running advertising campaigns was \"Grant Hill Drinks Sprite\" (overlapping its \"Obey Your Thirst\" campaign), in which Hill's abilities, and Sprite's importance in giving him his abilities, were humorously exaggerated.<ref>[http://www.advertisementave.com/tv/ad.asp?adid=116 A Better Basketball Player?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013132126/http://advertisementave.com/tv/ad.asp?adid=116 |date=October 13, 2007 }}, AdvertisementAve.com</ref>\n* Hill was a spokesperson for [[McDonald's]] restaurant, watchmaker [[TAG Heuer]] and sportswear companies [[Fila (company)|Fila]], and later [[Adidas]] and [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n* As of 2014, Hill has also appeared in ads for [[AT&T]] along with his wife Tamia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tamia & Grant Hill in New AT&T Commercial|url=http://csm21ent.com/2014/03/28/tamia-grant-hill-in-new-att-commercial/|publisher=Chris Smith Management / 21 Entertainment Group|accessdate=May 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522035157/http://csm21ent.com/2014/03/28/tamia-grant-hill-in-new-att-commercial/|archive-date=May 22, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==In television and film==\n* In 1995, Hill appeared in an episode of the [[Fox Broadcasting Network|FOX]] sitcom ''[[Living Single]]''.  In the episode, Hill (portraying himself) has a whirlwind romance with magazine owner/publisher Khadijah James ([[Queen Latifah]]).{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n* In 1998, he was in an episode of ''[[Home Improvement (TV series)|Home Improvement]]'' on the show inside a show ''Tool Time''.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n* Hill is featured in the video of the song \"[[Rockstar (Nickelback song)|Rockstar]]\" by [[Nickelback]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n* Hill presented an award at the [[1995 MTV Video Music Awards]] with talk show host [[Ricki Lake]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n* The March 13, 2011 airing of the [[ESPN films]] ''[[30 for 30]]'' documentary ''[[The Fab Five (film)|The Fab Five]]'' sparked national outrage, leading up to a series of media exchanges between members of the press and NCAA players in forums such as ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' and ''[[The Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=6202585 |title=The Fab Five: Hating Duke |accessdate=March 18, 2011 |date=March 10, 2011 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316171652/http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=6202585 |archivedate=March 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/jalen-roses-comments-on-race-in-espn-documentary-are-misguided/2011/03/12/ABFHbLS_story.html|title=Jalen Rose's comments on race in ESPN documentary are misguided|accessdate=March 17, 2011|date=March 13, 2011|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Reid, Jason}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thequad.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/16/grant-hills-response-to-jalen-rose/|title=Grant Hill's Response to Jalen Rose|accessdate=March 17, 2011|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Hill, Grant}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/dailyfix/2011/03/16/fab-five-member-responds-to-hill/|title=Fab Five Member Responds to Hill|accessdate=March 18, 2011|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Everson, Darren}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/42117791/ns/sports-college_basketball/|title=Hill Takes Issue In Fab Five Flap|accessdate=March 17, 2011|date=March 16, 2011|publisher=[[MSNBC]]}}{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2011/03/16/sports-bkc-fab-five-hill_8359957.html|title=Hill Takes Issue In Fab Five Flap|accessdate=March 17, 2011|date=March 16, 2011|work=[[Forbes]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110406054349/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2011/03/16/sports-bkc-fab-five-hill_8359957.html|archivedate=April 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and family==\nHill is the son of former NFL football player [[Calvin Hill]] and his wife, Janet Hill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/grant-hill-i-was-fortunate-but-that-didnt-necessarily-help-in-the-basketball-world/|title=Grant Hill: \u2018I was fortunate, but that didn\u2019t necessarily help in the basketball world\u2019|first=Marc J.|last=Spears|date=September 7, 2018}}</ref> He was born in Dallas, Texas and raised in the Washington, DC area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/cowboys/2015/04/03/hot-air-when-ex-cowboy-calvin-hill-was-unprepared-for-birth-of-son-grant-roger-staubach-came-through-again/|title=Hot Air: When ex-Cowboy Calvin Hill was 'unprepared' for birth of son Grant, Roger Staubach came through again|date=April 3, 2015|website=Dallas News}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], Hill was introduced to Canadian singer [[Tamia]] by [[Anita Baker]]. Hill and Tamia married on July 24, 1999. Their daughter, Myla Grace Hill, was born on January 23, 2002. On August 9, 2007, Tamia gave birth to their second daughter, Lael Rose Hill.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} The family resides in [[Windermere, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Disney reshaped mansion landscape for Orlando |date=December 23, 2016 |work=Orlando Sentinel |first=Mary |last=Shanklin |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/classified/realestate/os-orlando-mansions-20161219-story.html }}</ref>\n\nAfter contracting a life-threatening [[Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus|methicillin-resistant ''Staphylococcus aureus'']] (MRSA) infection in 2003,<ref>[http://www.stopmrsanow.org/granthill.html Grant Hill] at Stop MRSA Now!</ref> Hill became an advocate for the awareness and prevention of MRSA and has appeared in public service announcements for Stop MRSA Now!, a non-profit organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stopmrsanow.org/|title=Stop MRSA Now!|website=www.stopmrsanow.org}}</ref>{{better source|date=November 2019}}\n\nHill earned his [[bachelor's degree]] from Duke University with a double major in history and political science.<ref name=\"Eilerson2013\">{{cite news |url=http://www.fairfaxtimes.com/article/20130628/SPORTS/130629218/1061/grant-hill-pursues-life-beyond-basketball&template=fairfaxTimes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701231832/http://www.fairfaxtimes.com/article/20130628/SPORTS/130629218/1061/grant-hill-pursues-life-beyond-basketball%26template%3DfairfaxTimes |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 1, 2013 |title=Grant Hill pursues life beyond basketball Former South Lakes High star reflects back on roots in Reston |newspaper=[[Fairfax Times]] |first=Nick |last=Eilerson |date=June 28, 2013 |access-date=November 22, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Charitable activities===\n* Hill had been a Vice-Chairman for the Board of Directors of the Special Olympic World Summer Games in 1999 which were held in Durham, Raleigh and Chapel Hill, North Carolina.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://granthill.com/giving-back/national.php Giving Back to the Community] at Hill's official website</ref>{{better source|date=November 2019}}\n* Grant Hill, his mother Janet Hill and grandmother Vivian McDonald established a scholarship at the [[Dillard University]] in [[New Orleans]]. This scholarship is in memory of Hill's grandfather, who supported this University consistently.<ref name=autogenerated1 />{{better source|date=November 2019}}\n* Hill was featured on a poster \"READ\" that supported libraries, literacy, and advocated reading.<ref name=autogenerated1 />{{better source|date=November 2019}}\n* Hill contributed to the [[day care center]] established by his father, Calvin Hill, in New Haven, Connecticut in 1972, by donating funds. This day care center was established after Calvin graduated from Yale University and the goal was helping children and families in the local community.<ref name=autogenerated1 />{{better source|date=November 2019}}\n* Hill funded an organization in his hometown of [[Reston, Virginia]], that helps needy students of any age pursue education.<ref name=autogenerated1 />{{better source|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Other interests===\n* Hill owns a substantial collection of [[African-American art]], centering on the work of [[Romare Bearden]] and [[Elizabeth Catlett]]. A selection of 46 works from the collection were featured in a touring exhibition at a number of American museums from 2003 to 2006. The exhibition was last shown at the [[Nasher Museum of Art]] at Hill's alma mater, Duke University.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n* Hill has established ties with the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. On the night Hill was drafted in the NBA, he received a congratulatory phone call from U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]]. Hill publicly supported [[John Kerry]]'s [[John Kerry presidential campaign, 2004|2004 presidential campaign]] and [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|2008 presidential bid]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===Regular season===\n\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1994}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1994\u201395 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 70 || 69 || 38.3 || .477 || .148 || .732 || 6.4 || 5.0 || '''1.8''' || '''.9''' || 19.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1995}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1995\u201396 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 80 || 80 || '''40.8''' || .462 || .192 || .751 || '''9.8''' || 6.9 || 1.3 || .6 || 20.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1996}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1996\u201397 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 80 || 80 || 39.3 || .496 || .303 || .711 || 9.0 || '''7.3''' || '''1.8''' || .6 || 21.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1997}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1997\u201398 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 81 || '''81''' || 40.7 || .452 || .143 || .740 || 7.7 || 6.8 || '''1.8''' || .7 || 21.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1998\u201399 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 50 || 50 || 37.0 || .479 || .000 || .752 || 7.1 || 6.0 || 1.6 || .5 || 21.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1999|trunc=y}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1999\u20132000 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| 74 || 74 || 37.5 || .489 || .347 || .795 || 6.6 || 5.2 || 1.4 || .6 || '''25.8'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:le