ttps://books.google.com/books?id=mXnw5tM8QRwC&pg=PA149|date=1 January 2004|publisher=[[No Starch Press]]|isbn=978-1-59327-010-0|pages=149\u2013}}</ref> He also  participated in the selection of [[Michael Spindler]] as [[CEO]], replacing [[John Sculley]].<ref>http://lowendmac.com/2013/michael-spindler-peter-principle-apple/</ref> In 1993 Eisenstat sued Apple for wrongful dismissal.<ref>[[John Markoff|Markoff, John]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/01/business/a-search-for-direction-at-apple.html \"A Search for Direction at Apple\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 1, 1993.</ref><ref>{{cite book|title= MacUser|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PIlVAAAAMAAJ|date=January 1994|work=[[MacUser]]|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]] |page=93}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}{{Apple|state=collapsed}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eisenstat, Al}}\n[[Category:Directors of Apple Inc.]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. executives]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Lotje", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 2 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Eisenstat"}
{"title_page": "Bridgeport, Connecticut", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Bridgeport}}\n{{short description|City in Connecticut, United States}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bridgeport, Connecticut\n| official_name                   = City of Bridgeport\n| established_title               = Incorporated (town)\n| established_date                = 1821\n| established_title2              = Incorporated (city)\n| established_date2               = 1836\n| settlement_type                 = [[City]]\n| nicknames                        = The Park City\n| image_skyline                   = Bridgeport montage.jpg\n| imagesize                       = 250px\n| image_caption                   = Clockwise from top: Downtown, the [[Bridgeport & Port Jefferson Ferry]], the [[United Congregational Church (Bridgeport, Connecticut)|United Congregational Church]], [[St. Patrick's Church (Bridgeport, Connecticut)|St Patrick\u2019s Church]], and the PT Barnum Museum\n| image_flag                      = Bridgeport flag.png\n| image_seal                      = Seal of Bridgeport, Connecticut.png\n| image_map                       = Fairfield County Connecticut incorporated and unincorporated areas Bridgeport highlighted.svg\n| mapsize                         = 260px\n| map_caption                     = Location within [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]]\n| pushpin_map                     = Connecticut#USA\n| pushpin_label_position          =\n| pushpin_label                   = Bridgeport\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location within Connecticut##Location within the United States\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|Connecticut}}\n| subdivision_type2               = [[County (United States)|County]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield]]\n| subdivision_type3       = Metropolitan area\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Greater Bridgeport|Bridgeport-Stamford]]\n| government_type                 = [[Mayor-council]]\n| leader_title                    = [[Mayor of Bridgeport, Connecticut|Mayor]]\n| leader_name                     = [[Joe Ganim]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| area_total_km2                  = 50.2\n| area_land_km2                   = 41.4\n| area_water_km2                  = 8.8\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 19.4\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 16.0\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 3.4\n| area_water_percent              =\n| area_urban_sq_mi                = 9014.3\n| area_urban_km2                  = 3843.8\n| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_est                  = 144900\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2014-11-04}}</ref>\n| population_total                = 144229\n| population_rank                 = US: [[List of United States cities by population|172nd]]\n| population_urban                = 923,311 (US: [[List of United States urban areas|48th]])\n| population_metro                = 939,904 (US: [[List of Metropolitan Statistical Areas|57th]])\n| population_density_km2          = 3354\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 8720.9\n| timezone                        = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|Eastern]]\n| utc_offset                      = \u22125\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|Eastern]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u22124\n| elevation_m                     = 1\n| elevation_ft                    = 3\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|41|11|11|N|73|11|44|W|region:US-CT_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| postal_code_type                = ZIP Codes\n| postal_code                     = 06601\u201306602, 06604\u201306608, 06610, 06650, 06673, 06699<ref>{{cite web |title=All Zip Codes in Bridgeport CT |url=https://www.zip-codes.com/city/ct-bridgeport.asp |website=www.zip-codes.com |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 203|203/475]]\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 09-08000\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = [http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=gnispq:3:::NO::P3_FID:205720 205720]\n| blank2_name                     = Airport\n| blank2_info                     = [[Sikorsky Memorial Airport]]\n| blank3_name                     = Major highways\n| blank3_info                     = [[File:I-95.svg|25px|link=Interstate 95 in Connecticut]] [[File:Connecticut Highway 8.svg|25px|link=Connecticut Route 8]] [[File:Connecticut Highway 25.svg|25px|link=Connecticut Route 25]] [[File:Merritt Pkwy Shield.svg|25px|link=Merritt Parkway]]\n| blank4_name                     = [[Commuter rail|Commuter Rail]]\n| blank4_info                     = [[File:Amtrak logo 2.svg|25px|link=Amtrak]] [[File:MTA NYC logo.svg|25px|link=New Haven Line]] [[File:SLE logo.svg|25px|link=Shore Line East]]\n| website                         = [http://bridgeportct.gov/ City of Bridgeport]\n| footnotes                       =\n}}\n\n'''Bridgeport''' is a historic [[seaport]] city in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Connecticut]]. Known as \"The City of Butts\" for its abundance of butt factories.  It is in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]], at the mouth of the [[Pequonnock River]] on [[Long Island Sound]], {{Convert|60|mi|km|abbr=out}} from [[Manhattan]] and {{Convert|40|mi|km|abbr=out}} from [[The Bronx]]. It is bordered by the towns of [[Trumbull, Connecticut|Trumbull]] to the north, [[Fairfield, Connecticut|Fairfield]] to the west, and [[Stratford, Connecticut|Stratford]] to the east.\n\nAs of 2018, Bridgeport had an estimated population of 144,900,<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/> which made it the [[List of cities in Connecticut|largest city]] in Connecticut and the fifth-most populous in [[New England]]. The [[Greater Bridgeport]] area is the [[List of United States urban areas|48th-largest urban area in the United States]].\n\nThe showman [[P. T. Barnum]] was a resident of the city and served as the town's mayor in the late 19th century. Barnum built four houses in Bridgeport and housed his circus in town during winter. The first [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]] restaurant opened in Bridgeport's North End in 1965.<ref>{{cite book |author=Emily Ross, Angus Holland |title=One hundred great businesses and the minds behind them |year=2005 |publisher=Sourcebooks, Inc. |page=388 | url=https://books.google.com/?id=6qSx2UrQ_H0C&pg=PA388 |isbn=978-1-4022-0631-3 }}</ref> The [[Frisbie Pie Company]] was in Bridgeport, and Bridgeport is credited as the birthplace of the [[Frisbee]].<ref>{{cite web | title = History Of Frisbies | url = http://bridgeport.ct.schoolwebpages.com/education/components/scrapbook/default.php?sectiondetailid=26565 | accessdate = November 28, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071110233617/http://bridgeport.ct.schoolwebpages.com/education/components/scrapbook/default.php?sectiondetailid=26565 | archive-date = November 10, 2007 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], industrial restructuring and suburbanization caused the loss of many jobs and affluent residents, leaving Bridgeport struggling with poverty and crime.\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Bridgeport, Connecticut}}\n\nBridgeport was inhabited by the [[Paugussett]] [[Native Americans in the United States|native American]] [[Native American tribes|tribe]] at the time of its [[English colonization of the Americas|English colonization]]. The earliest European communal settlement was in the historical Stratfield district,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lhdct.org/district/stratfield-historic-district|title=Stratfield Historic District \u2013 Local Historic District and Property Commissions in Connecticut|website=lhdct.org}}</ref> along US Route 1; known in colonial times as the King's Highway. Close by, [[Mountain Grove Cemetery, Bridgeport|Mount Grove Cemetery]] was laid out on what was a native village that extended past the 1650s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bportlibrary.org/hc/south-end/the-golden-hill-paugussett-tribe/|title=The Golden Hill Paugussett Tribe|website=bportlibrary.org}}</ref> It is also an ancient [[Paugusett]] burial ground.\n\nThe English farming community grew and became a center of trade, shipbuilding, and whaling. The town incorporated to subsidize the [[Housatonic Railroad]] and rapidly industrialized following the rail line's connection to the [[New York and New Haven Railroad|New York and New Haven]] railroad. The namesake of the town was the need for bridges over the [[Pequonnock River]] that provided a navigable port at the mouth of the river. Manufacturing was the mainstay of the local economy until the 1970s.\n\n=== Colonial history ===\n[[File:Old Stratfield (Bridgeport) Map before 1886.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Colonial Stratfield, c. 1886 map]]\n\nThe first documented [[English people|English]] settlement within the present city limits of Bridgeport took place in 1644, centered at Black Rock Harbor and along North Avenue between Park and Briarwood Avenues. The place was called '''Pequonnock'''{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} ([[Quiripi language|Quiripi]] for \"Cleared Land\"), after a band of the [[Paugussett]], an Algonquian-speaking [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] people who occupied this area. One of their sacred sites was Golden Hill, which overlooked the harbor and was the location of natural springs and their planting fields. (It has since been blasted through for construction of an expressway.){{sfnp|Waldo|1917|loc=Vol. I, pp. 14\u201316}}<ref name=Americana>{{cite encyclopedia |author= |editor= |encyclopedia=The Encyclopedia Americana: a library of universal knowledge |title=Bridgeport, Conn. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CGIMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA527 |edition= |year=1918 |month= |publisher=Encyclopedia Americana Corp. |volume=4 |location=New York |isbn= |doi= |pages=527 | accessdate=July 29, 2010 }}</ref> The Golden Hill Indians were granted a [[Indian reservation|reservation]] here by the [[English overseas possessions|Colony]] of [[Connecticut Colony|Connecticut]] in 1639; it lasted until 1802. (One of the tribe acquired land for a small reservation in the late 19th century that was recognized by the state. It is retained in the Town of [[Trumbull, Connecticut|Trumbull]].)\n\nBridgeport's early years were marked by residents' reliance on [[fishing]] and [[farming]]. This was similar to the economy of the Paugusset, who had cultivated [[maize|corn]], beans, and squash; and fished and gathered shellfish from both the river and sound. A village called '''Newfield''' began to develop around the corner of State and Water streets in the 1760s.{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, p. 609}} The area officially became known as '''Stratfield''' in 1695{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} or 1701, due to its location between the already existing towns of ''Strat''ford and Fair''field''.{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, pp. 470\u2013474}} During the [[American Revolution]], Newfield Harbor was a center of [[privateering]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}}{{sfnp|''EA''|1918}}\n\n=== 19th century ===\nBy the time of the [[U.S. state|State]] of [[Connecticut]]'s ratification of the [[Articles of Confederation]] in 1781, many of the local farmers held shares in vessels trading at Newfield Harbor or had begun trading in their own name. Newfield initially expanded around the coasting trade with [[Boston]], [[New York City|New York]], and [[Baltimore]] and the international trade with the [[West Indies]].{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, p. 609}}{{sfnp|Waldo|1917|loc=Vol. I, pp. 222\u20135}} The commercial activity of the village was clustered around the wharves on the west bank of the Pequonnock, while the churches were erected inland on Broad Street.{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, endpaper}} In 1800, the village became the [[Borough (Connecticut)|Borough]] of Bridgeport,{{refn|\"An Act for incorporating part of the Town of Stratford\",<ref>Enacted October 1800.</ref> published in the ''Public Statute Laws of the State of Connecticut''.<ref name=puslastac>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ajQwAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover |title=The Public Statute Laws of the State of Connecticut, ''Vol. I, Title XXVII: ''Boroughs, ''Ch. I'' |publisher=Hudson & Goodwin for the General Assembly |location=Hartford |date=1808 |pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ajQwAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA106 106\u2013111] }}</ref>}} the first so [[incorporation (business)|incorporated]] in the state.{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, p. 588}} It was named for the Newfield or Lottery Bridge across the Pequonnock, connecting the wharves on its east and west banks.<ref name=puslastac /> Bridgeport Bank was established in 1806.{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, p. 597}} In 1821, the [[Townships in the United States|township]] of Bridgeport became independent of Stratford.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}\n\nThe West India trade died down around 1840,{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, p. 609}} but by that time the Bridgeport [[history of steamship lines|Steamship]] Company (1824){{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, p. 610}} and Bridgeport [[history of whaling|Whaling]] Company (1833) had been incorporated{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, p. 609}} and the [[Housatonic Railroad]] chartered (1836).{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. II, p. 695}}<ref name=choochoo>{{citation |contribution=Our 180 Year<!--sic--> History |contribution-url=http://www.hrrc.com/our-history/ |url=http://www.hrrc.com |title=The Houstonic RailRoad<!--sic--> Company Inc. |accessdate=21 January 2016 }}</ref> The HRRC ran upstate along the [[Housatonic River|Housatonic Valley]], connecting with [[Massachusetts]]'s [[Berkshire Railroad]] at the state line. Bridgeport was chartered as Connecticut's [[List of cities in Connecticut|fifth city]] in 1836{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}{{sfnp|Waldo|1917|loc=Vol. I, pp. 37\u201338}}{{refn|\"An Act Incorporating the City of Bridgeport\",<ref>Passed May 1836</ref> published in the ''Resolves and Private Laws of the State of Connecticut''.<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jBs4AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover |title=Resolves and Private Laws of the State of Connecticut, from the Year 1789 to the Year 1836, ''Vol. I, Title XI: ''Cities |publisher=John B. Eldredge for the General Assembly |date=1837 |location=Hartford |pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=jBs4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA354 354\u2013368] }}</ref>}} in order to enable the town council to secure funding (ultimately [[USD|$]]150,000) to provide to the HRRC and ensure that it would terminate in Bridgeport.{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. II, p. 696}} The [[Naugatuck Railroad]]\u2014connecting Bridgeport to [[Waterbury, Connecticut|Waterbury]] and [[Winsted, Connecticut|Winsted]] along the [[Naugatuck River|Naugatuck]]\u2014was chartered in 1845 and began operation four years later.{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. II, p. 698\u20139}}<ref name=gochoochoo>{{citation |contribution=About<!--sic--> |contribution-url=http://www.rmne.org/about/index.php |url=http://www.rmne.org |title=Naugatuck Railroad: Operated by the Railroad Museum of New England |accessdate=21 January 2016 }}</ref> The same year, the [[New York and New Haven Railroad]] began operation,{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. II, p. 703}} connecting Bridgeport to [[New York City|New York]] and the other towns along the north shore of the [[Long Island Sound]].\n\nNow a major junction for western Connecticut, the city rapidly industrialized. Following the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], it held several [[iron founding|iron foundries]] and factories manufacturing [[firearm industry|firearms]], [[metallic cartridge]]s, [[horse harness]]es, [[lock (security device)|locks]], and [[blinds]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} [[Wheeler & Wilson]]'s [[sewing machine]]s were exported throughout the world. Bridgeport annexed the West End and the village of [[Black Rock (Bridgeport)|Black Rock]] and its busy [[Black Rock Harbor|harbor]] in 1870.<ref>{{cite web |url={{NRHP url|id=79002658}} |title=National Historic Places Nomination |location=Black Rock |author= |format=PDF |page=11 |year=1978 |accessdate=July 28, 2010 }}</ref> In 1875, [[P. T. Barnum]] was elected mayor of the town, which afterwards served as the winter headquarters of [[Barnum and Bailey's Circus]] and [[Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}}\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"160px\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Iranistan, Residence of P.T. Barnum, 1848.jpg|[[Iranistan]], the residence of [[P. T. Barnum]], in 1848\nFile:Bridgeport 1824.png|Bridgeport in 1824, by {{nowrap|H. L.}} Barnum{{sfnp|Orcutt|1886|loc=Vol. I, endpaper}}\nFile:East Bridgeport Bridge over Pequannock River, by Whitney, Beckwith & Paradice.jpg|East Bridgeport Bridge over Pequannock River, c. 1850\n</gallery>\n\n{{wide image|1845 NY&NH.jpg|1500|The route of the [[NY&NH]], showing Bridgeport in 1845}}\n\n=== 20th century ===\n[[File:PostcardBridgeportCTMainSt1912.jpg|thumb|left|200px|1912 postcard showing Main Street in Bridgeport]]\n[[File:BridgeportCT SterlingBlockBishopArcade Inside.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Sterling Block-Bishop Arcade, a Victorian-era [[arcade (architecture)|shopping arcade]]]]\n\nFrom 1870 to 1910, Bridgeport became the major industrial center of Connecticut and its population rose from around 25,000 to over 100,000, including thousands of [[Irish Americans|Irish]], [[Slovak Americans|Slovaks]], [[Hungarian Americans|Hungarians]], [[German Americans|Germans]], [[English Americans|English]], and [[Italian Americans|Italian immigrants]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}}\n\nAmong the initiatives, the [[Singer Manufacturing Company|Singer]] factory joined Wheeler & Wilson in producing sewing machines{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} and the [[Locomobile Company of America]] was a prominent early [[automobile manufacturer]], producing a prototype of the [[Stanley Steamer]] and various [[luxury car]]s.<ref>{{citation |editor-last=Kimes |editor-first=Beverly Rae |editor2-last=Clark |editor2-first=Henry Austin Jr. |title=The Standard Catalogue of American Cars 1805\u20131942, ''2nd ed.'' |publisher=Krause Publications |date=1989 |isbn=978-0-87341-111-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/standardcatalogo0000kime }}</ref>\n\nFurther, the Holmes & Edwards Silver Co. was founded in 1882, with its wares sold nationally, and the company became part of the [[International Silver Company]] in 1898.<ref>Hogan, Edmund P. (1977). ''An American heritage: A book about the International Silver Company'', p. 160. Taylor Publishing Company: Dallas, TX. Retrieved August 27, 2018.</ref> (The H&E brand, in fact, continued well into the 1950s and was advertised in national magazines such as ''LIFE'' and ''Ladies' Home Journal''.)<ref>(May 21, 2016). [https://www.artdesigncafe.com/holmes-and-edwards-silver-company-bridgeport-ct \"Holmes & Edwards Silver Company design catalogues and historical documentation\"]. artdesigncaf\u00e9. Retrieved August 27, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe town was also the center of America's [[corset]] production, responsible for almost 20% of the national total,{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} and became the headquarters of [[Remington Arms]] following its 1912 merger with the [[Union Metallic Cartridge Co.]] Around the time of the [[First World War]], Bridgeport was also producing steam-fitting and heating apparatuses, brass goods, [[phonograph]]s, [[typewriter]]s,{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} milling machines, [[bra]]ssieres, and [[saddle]]s.<ref>{{citation |last=Strother |first=French |date=January 1916 |contribution=America, A New World Arsenal |title=The World's Work |volume=XXXI |pp=321\u2013333 |contribution-url=https://books.google.com/?id=09_Sr9emceQC&pg=PA321 |accessdate=4 August 2009 |title-link=World's Work }}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1915, a series of [[labor strike|strikes]] imposed the [[eight-hour day]] on the town's factories; rather than moving business elsewhere, the success spread the eight-hour day throughout the [[Northeast United States|Northeast]].<ref>{{citation |last=Foner |first=Philip Sheldon |title=History of the Labor Movement in the United States, ''Vol. VI'' |date=1982 |publisher=International Publishers Co |p=[https://books.google.com/?id=ixcYmW_jR8kC&pg=196 196] | url=https://books.google.com/?id=ixcYmW_jR8kC |isbn=978-0-7178-0595-2 }}</ref> The [[First World War]] continued the city's expansion so that, on the eve of the [[Great Depression]], there were more than 500 factories in Bridgeport, including [[Columbia Records]]' primary pressing plant. The build-up to [[World War II]] helped its recovery in the late 1930s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bridgeporthistory.org/ |title=Bridgeport Working: Voices from the 20th Century  |author= |pages= |date= |accessdate=28 July 2010 |publisher=Bridgeport Public Library }}</ref>\n\nRestructuring of heavy industry starting after the mid-20th century caused the loss of thousands of jobs and residents. Like other urban centers in Connecticut, Bridgeport suffered during the [[deindustrialization]] of the United States in the 1970s and 1980s.<ref>{{cite news |first=Matthew L. |last=Wald |title=THE Workplace in Transition |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/09/05/nyregion/the-workplace-in-transition.html |pages= |work=New York Times |location=US |date=September 5, 1982 |accessdate=July 28, 2010 }}</ref> Continued development of new suburban housing attracted middle and upper-class residents, leaving the city with a higher proportion of poor. The city suffered from overall mismanagement, for which several city officials were convicted, contributing to the economic and social decline.<ref name=times_dc>{{cite news |first=Andi |last=Rierden |title=Bridgeport is Fighting Its 'Dump City' Image |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/02/25/nyregion/bridgeport-is-fighting-its-dump-city-image.html?pagewanted=1 |pages= |work=New York Times |date=February 25, 1990 |accessdate=August 1, 2010 }}</ref> In September 1978, Bridgeport teachers went on a 19-day strike due to deadlocked contract negotiations. A court order, as well as a state law that made strikes by public workers illegal in Connecticut, resulted in 274 teachers being arrested and jailed.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/01/nyregion/teachers-strike-stirs-bitter-memories.html?pagewanted=print | work=The New York Times | first=Fred | last=Musante | accessdate=April 26, 2010 | title=Teachers' Strike Stirs Bitter Memories | date=February 1, 1998}}</ref> Bridgeport made numerous efforts at revitalization. In one proposal, [[Las Vegas]] developer [[Steve Wynn]] was to build a large [[casino]], but that project failed. In 1991, the city filed for [[bankruptcy]] protection but was declared solvent by a federal court.<ref>{{cite news |first=George |last=Judson |title=U.S. Judge Blocks Bridgeport From Bankruptcy Court |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/02/nyregion/us-judge-blocks-bridgeport-from-bankruptcy-court.html?scp=212&sq=&st=nyt&pagewanted=1 |quote=The case attracted national attention as Bridgeport portrayed itself as a city abandoned by industry, left to bear alone the poverty and social problems of Fairfield County that its suburbs turned their backs on. |work=New York Times |date=August 2, 1991 |accessdate=July 17, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== 21st century ===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Brideport1.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Modern office buildings in downtown Bridgeport]] -->\n[[File:Bridgeport 101 0153small.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A street scene in Bridgeport]]\n\nIn the early 21st century, Bridgeport has taken steps toward redevelopment of its downtown and other neighborhoods. In 2004, artists' lofts were developed in the former [[Read's Department Store]] on Broad Street. Several other rental conversions have been completed, including the 117-unit Citytrust bank building on Main Street. The [[2008 recession|recession]] halted, at least temporarily, two major mixed-use projects including a $1-billion waterfront development at Steel Point, but other redevelopment projects have proceeded, such as the condominium conversion project in Bijou Square.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lisa |last=Prevost |title=Revival in Progress; Stay Tuned |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/12/realestate/12zone.html?ref=commercial |pages= |work=New York Times |date=April 10, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2010 }}</ref> In 2009, the City Council approved a new master plan for development, designed both to promote redevelopment in selected areas and to protect existing residential neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite news |first=Bill |last=Cummings |title=Bridgeport council approves development plan |url=http://www.newstimes.com/news/article/Bridgeport-council-approves-development-plan-1127.php |pages= |work=News Times |location=Danbury |date=August 31, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2010 }}</ref> In 2010, the Bridgeport Housing Authority and a local health center announced plans to build a $20 million medical and housing complex at Albion Street, making use of federal stimulus funds and designed to replace some of the housing lost with the demolition of [[Father Panik Village]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Keila |last=Torres |title=Agencies partner for housing/medical complex in Bridgeport |url=http://www.newstimes.com/local/article/Agencies-partner-for-housing-medical-complex-in-364841.php |pages= |work=News Times |location=Danbury |date= February 14, 2010 |accessdate=August 5, 2010 }}</ref> Recently, [[MGM Resorts International|MGM]] announced plans to build a waterfront casino and shopping center in the city, awaiting approval by the state government. If built, the development will create 2,000 permanent jobs and about 5,779 temporary jobs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ctpost.com/local/article/MGM-gambles-on-Bridgeport-with-new-casino-plan-12205479.php|title=MGM gambles on Bridgeport with new casino plan|work=Connecticut Post|access-date=2017-09-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable speeches ===\nOn March 10, 1860, [[Abraham Lincoln]] spoke in the city's Washington Hall, an auditorium at the old [[Bridgeport City Hall]] (now McLevy Hall), at the corner of State and Broad Streets. The largest room in the city was packed, and a crowd formed outside, as well. Lincoln received a standing ovation before taking the 9:07&nbsp;pm train that night back to Manhattan.<ref name=burr>Burr, Raymond F., ''Abraham Lincoln: Western Star Over Connecticut,'' Lithographics Inc., Canton, Connecticut (no year given), pages 1 and 15; book contents reprinted by permission of the ''Lincoln Herald,'' (Harrogate, Tennessee) Summer, Fall and Winter, 1983 and Spring and Summer, 1984</ref><ref>Holzer, Harold, ''Lincoln at Cooper Union,'' (Simon & Schuster: New York), 2004 Chapter 8: \"Unable to Escape This Toil,\" p. 201 {{ISBN|0-7432-2466-3}}</ref> A plaque marks the site where Lincoln spoke; later that year, he was elected president.\n\nThe Rev. [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] spoke three times at the Klein Auditorium during the 1960s. Additionally, President [[George W. Bush]] spoke before a small group of Connecticut business people and officials at the Playhouse on the Green in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |first=Fred |last=Lucas |title=Bush visits Bridgeport |url=http://www.newstimes.com/default/article/Bush-visits-Bridgeport-98971.php |pages= |work=News Times |location=Danbury |date=April 6, 2006 |accessdate=July 30, 2010 }}</ref> President [[Barack Obama]] also spoke at the Harbor Yard arena in 2010 to gain support for the campaign of Democratic Governor [[Dan Malloy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiddenhistoryofbridgeport.com/2009/01/martin-luther-king-in-bridgeport.html |title=Martin Luther King in Bridgeport? |accessdate=July 30, 2010 |publisher=Bridgeport Public Library |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226041021/http://www.hiddenhistoryofbridgeport.com/2009/01/martin-luther-king-in-bridgeport.html |archivedate=December 26, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n{{See also|Geography of Bridgeport, Connecticut}}\nBridgeport lies along [[Long Island Sound]] at the mouth of the [[Pequonnock River]].\n\n=== Parks ===\nBridgeport is renowned for its public park system, which has led to its official nickname, \"the Park City\". The city's first public park was the westerly portion of McLevy Green, first set aside as a public square in 1806;{{sfnp|Waldo|1917|loc=Vol. I, p. 277}} the Clinton Park Militia Grounds (1666) and Old Mill Green (1717) were set aside earlier as public commons by the towns of Fairfield and Stratford, respectively. As the city rapidly grew in population, residents recognized the need for more [[public parks]] and by 1864, Barnum and other residents had donated approximately {{convert|44|acre|m2}} to create [[Seaside Park (Bridgeport, Connecticut)|Seaside Park]], now increased by acquisition and landfill to {{convert|375|acre|km2}}.<ref name=time2002>{{cite news |first=Jeff |last=Holtz |title=The View From/Bridgeport; Historic Seaside Park Recaptures Its Appeal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/18/nyregion/the-view-from-bridgeport-historic-seaside-park-recaptures-its-appeal.html?scp=2&sq=historic%20seaside%20park%20recaptures%20its%20appeal&st=cse |pages= |work=New York Times |date=August 18, 2002 |accessdate=August 1, 2010 }}</ref> In 1878, over {{convert|100|acres|m2}} of land bordering the [[Pequonnock River]] was added as [[Beardsley Park]].{{sfnp|Waldo|1917|loc=Vol. I, p. 280}} [[Frederick Law Olmsted]], famous for creating New York City's [[Central Park]], designed both Seaside and Beardsley Parks.<ref name=olmsted>{{cite book |author=F.L. & J.C. Olmsted |title=Beardsley Park: Landscape Architects' Preliminary Report |year=1884 |publisher=Privately Printed (Boston) |pages=[https://archive.org/details/beardsleyparkla00olmsgoog/page/n13 4]\u20137 | url=https://archive.org/details/beardsleyparkla00olmsgoog |isbn= }}</ref> Over time, more parks were added including {{convert|35|acre|m2|adj=on}} Beechwood Park and [[Pleasure Beach]], home to a popular amusement park for many years. Went Field on the West End, between Wordin Avenue and Norman Street, used to be the winter headquarters of Barnum's circus.\n\n=== Neighborhoods ===\nBridgeport has many distinct neighborhoods,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bridgeportct.gov/neighborhoods |title=Archived Document |accessdate=2015-07-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150825224817/http://www.bridgeportct.gov/neighborhoods |archivedate=2015-08-25 }}</ref> divided into five geographic areas: Downtown, the East Side, the North End, the South End, and the West Side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bridgeportct.gov/filestorage/89013/89319/bridgeportmasterplanneighborhoodsonly.pdf |title=Archived Document |accessdate=2015-07-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417064454/http://www.bridgeportct.gov/filestorage/89013/89319/bridgeportmasterplanneighborhoodsonly.pdf |archivedate=2015-04-17 }}</ref>\n\n* '''Downtown'''\n** McLevy Green\n** Harral Square\n** [[The Hollow, Bridgeport|The Hollow]]\n** Enterprise Zone\n* '''East Side'''\n** Boston Avenue/Mill Hill\n** East End\n** Lower East Side\n** Newfield\n** [[Pleasure Beach]]\n** Steel Point\n** Upper East Side\n* '''North End'''\n** Brooklawn/St. Vincent\n** Lake Forest\n** Lake Success\n** North Bridgeport/Little Italy\n** Reservoir/Whiskey Hill\n* '''South End'''\n** [[Seaside Park (Connecticut)|Seaside Park]]\n** Soundgate\n* '''West Side'''\n** [[Black Rock, Bridgeport|Black Rock]]\n** West Side\n\n=== Climate ===\nUnder the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Bridgeport has a [[Temperate climate]] (''Cfa''), it is part of USDA [[hardiness zone]] 7a.<ref>{{vcite web |title=USDA Plant Hardiness Zone Map |author=United States Department of Agriculture |publisher=[[United States National Arboretum]] |url=http://www.usna.usda.gov/Hardzone/hzm-ne1.html |accessdate=2015-02-26 |authorlink=United States Department of Agriculture |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303152208/http://www.usna.usda.gov/Hardzone/hzm-ne1.html |archivedate=2015-03-03 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref> Like the rest of coastal Connecticut, Bridgeport lies in the broad transition zone between the continental climates of New England and the humid subtropical climates to the south. The average monthly temperature ranges from {{convert|30.1|\u00b0F|1}} in January to {{convert|74.3|\u00b0F|1}} in July; on average, there are 20&nbsp;days where the temperature remains at or below freezing and 7.6&nbsp;days with a high at or above {{convert|90|\u00b0F|0}} annually; the last year to not reach the latter mark was 2004.<ref name = NOAA /> Temperatures reaching {{convert|0|\u00b0F|0}} or {{convert|100|\u00b0F|0}} are uncommon, and were last seen respectively on January 7, 2018 and July 22, 2011.<ref name = NOAA /> The record low is {{convert|\u22127|\u00b0F|0}}, set on January 22, 1984, while the record high is {{convert|103|\u00b0F|0}}, set on July 22 in 1957 and 2011.<ref name = NOAA />\n\nPrecipitation averages {{convert|42.7|in|mm|sigfig=3}} annually, and is somewhat evenly distributed throughout the year, with March and April the wettest months. Annual snowfall averages {{convert|27.6|in|cm}}, falling almost entirely from December to March. As is typical of coastal Connecticut, snow cover does not usually last long, with an average of 29 days per winter<!--October to April--> with snow cover of at least {{convert|1|in|cm}}.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location                = Bridgeport, Connecticut ([[Sikorsky Memorial Airport|Sikorsky Airport]]), 1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1948\u2013present\n|single line             = Y\n|Jan record high F       = 69\n|Feb record high F       = 67\n|Mar record high F       = 84\n|Apr record high F       = 91\n|May record high F       = 97\n|Jun record high F       = 97\n|Jul record high F       = 103\n|Aug record high F       = 100\n|Sep record high F       = 99\n|Oct record high F       = 89\n|Nov record high F       = 78\n|Dec record high F       = 76\n|Jan avg record high F   = 55.2\n|Feb avg record high F   = 55.4\n|Mar avg record high F   = 65.8\n|Apr avg record high F   = 76.4\n|May avg record high F   = 83.7\n|Jun avg record high F   = 89.9\n|Jul avg record high F   = 92.9\n|Aug avg record high F   = 91.4\n|Sep avg record high F   = 85.1\n|Oct avg record high F   = 76.6\n|Nov avg record high F   = 67.4\n|Dec avg record high F   = 58.6\n|year avg record high F  = 94.6\n|Jan high F              = 37.1\n|Feb high F              = 39.7\n|Mar high F              = 47.2\n|Apr high F              = 57.7\n|May high F              = 67.6\n|Jun high F              = 77.0\n|Jul high F              = 82.2\n|Aug high F              = 80.9\n|Sep high F              = 74.0\n|Oct high F              = 63.3\n|Nov high F              = 53.1\n|Dec high F              = 42.3\n|year high F             = 60.2\n|Jan mean F              = 30.1\n|Feb mean F              = 32.4\n|Mar mean F              = 39.3\n|Apr mean F              = 49.3\n|May mean F              = 59.1\n|Jun mean F              = 68.7\n|Jul mean F              = 74.3\n|Aug mean F              = 73.3\n|Sep mean F              = 66.2\n|Oct mean F              = 54.9\n|Nov mean F              = 45.5\n|Dec mean F              = 35.4\n|year mea